    "notes": "Chichewa/Nyanja (Chicheŵa). Bantu language; official language of Malawi (as Chichewa) and spoken in Zambia (as Nyanja), Mozambique (Tete province), and Zimbabwe. ~15 million speakers. KEY FEATURES: (1) FIVE-VOWEL SYSTEM: a/e/i/o/u; e=[ɛ], o=[ɔ]. (2) PRENASALIZED STOPS: mb/mp/nd/nk/nt/nz — phonemic sequences functioning as single onset consonants. (3) SYLLABIC NASALS: m- and n- noun class prefixes are syllabic (/m̩/, /n̩/) before consonants. (4) NG vs NG': <ng'> = [ŋ] (bare velar nasal), <ng> = [ŋɡ] prenasalized. (5) LABIALIZED CONSONANTS: bw/gw/kw/mw/nw/pw/tw/zw are phonemic. (6) ASPIRATED STOPS: kh/ph/th = [kʰ/pʰ/tʰ], phonemic. (7) TONES: lexical tone (H/L), not marked in standard orthography. (8) OPEN SYLLABLE PREFERENCE: most syllables end in vowel.",
